  <introduction>
    <p>
      Introduction goes here.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <ul>
    <li>
      <p>
        Just as curves can be written as functions of a parameter <m>t</m>, surfaces can be written as functions of two parameters, often called <m>u</m> and <m>v</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        A few examples:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              Sphere of radius <m>\rho</m>:
              <me>
                \bv r(\theta,\phi)=(x,y,z)=(\rho\sin\phi\cos\theta,\rho\sin\phi\sin\theta,\rho\cos\phi)
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Helicoid:
              <me>
                \bv r(u,v)=(x,y,z)=(v\cos u,v\sin u,au)
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Surface of revolution about <m>x</m>-axis:
              <me>
                \bv r(u,v)=(x,y,z)=(u,f(u)\cos v,f(u)\sin v)
              </me>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
        For all of these, <m>(u,v)</m> are points of some domain <m>D</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Surface area element:
        <me>
          \dd{\cl{S}}=\norm{\pdv{\bv{r}}{u}\times\pdv{\bv{r}}{v}}\dd{A}
        </me>
        Here, <m>\dd{\cl{A}}=\dd{u}\dd{v}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Surface area:
        <me>
          S=\iint_{\cl{S}}\dd{S}=\iint_{D}\norm{\pdv{\bv{r}}{u}\times\pdv{\bv{r}}{v}}\dd{A}
        </me>
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Similarly to with line integrals, we can extend this to make the surface integral of a function over that surface:
        <me>
          S=\iint_{\cl{S}}f\dd{S}=\iint_{D}f(\bv r(u,v))\norm{\pdv{\bv{r}}{u}\times\pdv{\bv{r}}{v}}\dd{A}
        </me>
        Notice this is just the next level up of what we already do with line integrals.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        If <m>f</m> is density, then we can compute mass, center of mass, moment of inertia, etc.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <p>
        Again, if <m>\bv r(u,v)=(x,y,z)</m>, and the Jacobian is
        <me>
          \bv J=\begin{bmatrix}\DS\pdv{x}{u} \amp \DS\pdv{x}{v}\\[2 ex] \DS\pdv{y}{u} \amp \DS\pdv{y}{v}\\[2 ex] \DS\pdv{z}{u} \amp \DS\pdv{z}{v}\end{bmatrix}\text{,}
        </me>
        then we end up with <m>\sqrt{\abs{\det(\bv J^T\bv J)}}=\norm{\DS\pdv{\bv{r}}{u}\times\dv{\bv{r}}{v}}</m>.
      </p>
    </li>
  </ul>
</section>
